    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="132"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d132">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/19747</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The French Chief of State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Pétain</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vichy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-16">January 16,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear President</hi>: I was happy to receive your New
                    Year’s message<note n="2" xml:id="d132fn2">Letter dated December 27, 1941; see
                            <ref target="frus1941v02#pg_205">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 205</ref>.</note> and at the same time
                    to have confirmation of the interest which you had felt in our recent
                        conversations<note n="3" xml:id="d132fn3">See <ref
                            target="frus1941v02#pg_196">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 196</ref> ff.</note> with Admiral
                        Leahy.<note n="4" xml:id="d132fn4">Adm. William D. Leahy, American
                        Ambassador in France.</note> During the course of these conversations,
                    French policy was clearly defined both by me and by the Vice President of the
                        Council<note n="5" xml:id="d132fn5">Jean François Darlan.</note> and I see
                    with keen satisfaction that the Government of the United States understands the
                    position of the French Government in the present conflict.</p>
                <p>The sentiments which you were good enough to express to me on this occasion
                    respond to those which the French people feel for the American nation and you
                    may be assured of the fidelity of the French to the traditions which you
                    invoke.</p>
                <p>I was very much touched by the good wishes which your message brought me; I beg
                    you to find here the expression of my thanks and the renewal of my best
                    wishes.</p>
                <p>Please accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ph. Pétain</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
